## 2. Enable required APIs

One-time, idempotent. Takes ~2 minutes.

```bash
gcloud services enable \
  run.googleapis.com \
  cloudbuild.googleapis.com \
  artifactregistry.googleapis.com \
  sqladmin.googleapis.com \
  secretmanager.googleapis.com \
  cloudtasks.googleapis.com \
  cloudscheduler.googleapis.com \
  storage.googleapis.com \
  iam.googleapis.com \
  iamcredentials.googleapis.com \
  cloudtrace.googleapis.com \
  logging.googleapis.com \
  monitoring.googleapis.com
```

**Verify:** `gcloud services list --enabled | grep -E "run|sql|secret|tasks"` shows all four.

---

## 3. One-time GCP infrastructure

### 3.1 Service accounts

Three accounts, each with the minimum role set. **Never reuse one for
multiple roles** — the auditability of who-did-what depends on this.

```bash
# Runtime service account (Cloud Run uses this to access GCS / Cloud SQL / Tasks)
gcloud iam service-accounts create {{PROJECT_NAME}}-app \
  --display-name="{{PROJECT_NAME}} runtime"

# Deploy service account (GitHub Actions uses this via Workload Identity)
gcloud iam service-accounts create {{PROJECT_NAME}}-deploy \
  --display-name="{{PROJECT_NAME}} CI/CD"

# Scheduler service account (Cloud Scheduler uses this to call admin endpoints)
gcloud iam service-accounts create {{PROJECT_NAME}}-scheduler \
  --display-name="{{PROJECT_NAME}} cron caller"
```

Grant runtime account the roles it needs:

```bash
APP_SA="{{PROJECT_NAME}}-app@${PROJECT_ID}.iam.gserviceaccount.com"

for role in \
  roles/cloudsql.client \
  roles/storage.objectAdmin \
  roles/cloudtasks.enqueuer \
  roles/secretmanager.secretAccessor \
  roles/cloudtrace.agent \
  roles/logging.logWriter \
  roles/monitoring.metricWriter ; do
  gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding "$PROJECT_ID" \
    --member="serviceAccount:${APP_SA}" \
    --role="$role" \
    --condition=None
done
```

Grant deploy account the roles it needs:

```bash
DEPLOY_SA="{{PROJECT_NAME}}-deploy@${PROJECT_ID}.iam.gserviceaccount.com"

for role in \
  roles/run.admin \
  roles/artifactregistry.writer \
  roles/cloudbuild.builds.editor \
  roles/iam.serviceAccountUser \
  roles/storage.admin ; do
  gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding "$PROJECT_ID" \
    --member="serviceAccount:${DEPLOY_SA}" \
    --role="$role" \
    --condition=None
done
```

Scheduler account needs only the run-invoker role — but only on **this
service**, not project-wide. We grant that in §7 after the service exists.

### 3.2 Artifact Registry

```bash
gcloud artifacts repositories create "$REPOSITORY" \
  --repository-format=docker \
  --location="$REGION" \
  --description="{{PROJECT_NAME}} container images"
```

**Verify:** `gcloud artifacts repositories list --location="$REGION"`.

### 3.3 Cloud Storage

```bash
gcloud storage buckets create "gs://${GCS_BUCKET}" \
  --location="$REGION" \
  --uniform-bucket-level-access \
  --default-storage-class=STANDARD
```

Lifecycle policy — delete intermediate objects after 7 days (delete
immediately post-processing in app code; this is a backstop for crash
cases):

```bash
cat >/tmp/lifecycle.json <<'EOF'
{
  "lifecycle": {
    "rule": [
      {
        "action": {"type": "Delete"},
        "condition": {"age": 7, "matchesPrefix": ["uploads/"]}
      }
    ]
  }
}
EOF
gcloud storage buckets update "gs://${GCS_BUCKET}" \
  --lifecycle-file=/tmp/lifecycle.json
```

**Verify:** `gcloud storage buckets describe "gs://${GCS_BUCKET}" | grep -i lifecycle`.

### 3.4 Cloud SQL Postgres

```bash
gcloud sql instances create "$SQL_INSTANCE" \
  --region="$REGION" \
  --database-version=POSTGRES_16 \
  --tier=db-f1-micro \
  --storage-size=10GB \
  --storage-type=SSD \
  --backup \
  --backup-start-time=03:00 \
  --enable-point-in-time-recovery
```

This takes ~6 minutes. While it runs, continue to §3.5.

Once it's up:

```bash
# Generate a strong password (alternative: use Secret Manager auto-generation)
DB_PASSWORD=$(openssl rand -base64 32 | tr -d '=+/' | head -c 32)
echo "DB_PASSWORD=$DB_PASSWORD"   # save this — you'll feed it into Secret Manager in §3.6

gcloud sql users create "$DB_USER" \
  --instance="$SQL_INSTANCE" \
  --password="$DB_PASSWORD"

gcloud sql databases create "$DB_NAME" --instance="$SQL_INSTANCE"
```

**Cloud SQL connection name** (you'll need this for the DATABASE_URL):

```bash
SQL_CONNECTION_NAME=$(gcloud sql instances describe "$SQL_INSTANCE" \
  --format='value(connectionName)')
echo "$SQL_CONNECTION_NAME"
# Example: my-project:europe-west1:{{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg
```

### 3.5 Cloud Tasks queue (skip if you don't use background jobs)

```bash
gcloud tasks queues create "$TASKS_QUEUE" \
  --location="$REGION" \
  --max-attempts=5 \
  --max-backoff=600s \
  --min-backoff=10s \
  --max-doublings=4 \
  --max-dispatches-per-second=10 \
  --max-concurrent-dispatches=20
```

**Verify:** `gcloud tasks queues describe "$TASKS_QUEUE" --location="$REGION"`.

### 3.6 Secret Manager

Create each secret your `cloud_run.yaml` references, then store its value.
**Run each `printf | gcloud secrets versions add` in a fresh shell line so
the secret isn't logged to history with `set -x` or pipe artifacts.**

```bash
# Helper — only used for the first version of each secret
create_secret() {
  local name="$1"
  gcloud secrets create "$name" --replication-policy=automatic 2>/dev/null || true
}

# Edit this list to match the secret names in your cloud_run.yaml
for s in \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-database-url \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-provider-token \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-webhook-secret \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-llm-api-key \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-stripe-secret-key \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-stripe-webhook-secret \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-cron-secret \
  {{PROJECT_NAME}}-sentry-dsn ; do
  create_secret "$s"
done

# Store values — run each line interactively so the secret stays out of history
read -rsp "LLM API key: " LLM_KEY  ; echo
printf '%s' "$LLM_KEY" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-llm-api-key --data-file=-

read -rsp "Auth provider token: " AUTH_TOKEN ; echo
printf '%s' "$AUTH_TOKEN" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-provider-token --data-file=-

# Webhook secret — generate locally, save both here and for the provider's webhook config
AUTH_WEBHOOK_SECRET=$(openssl rand -hex 32)
echo "AUTH_WEBHOOK_SECRET=$AUTH_WEBHOOK_SECRET"   # save this for §6
printf '%s' "$AUTH_WEBHOOK_SECRET" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-webhook-secret --data-file=-

# Cron secret — generate locally
CRON_SECRET=$(openssl rand -hex 32)
echo "CRON_SECRET=$CRON_SECRET"   # save this for §7
printf '%s' "$CRON_SECRET" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-cron-secret --data-file=-

# Stripe — fill in after §4
# Sentry DSN — fill in after §3.7

# DATABASE_URL — uses the password from §3.4
DATABASE_URL="postgresql+asyncpg://${DB_USER}:${DB_PASSWORD}@/${DB_NAME}?host=/cloudsql/${SQL_CONNECTION_NAME}"
printf '%s' "$DATABASE_URL" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-database-url --data-file=-
```

**Verify:**
```bash
for s in {{PROJECT_NAME}}-database-url {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-provider-token \
         {{PROJECT_NAME}}-auth-webhook-secret {{PROJECT_NAME}}-llm-api-key \
         {{PROJECT_NAME}}-cron-secret ; do
  versions=$(gcloud secrets versions list "$s" --format='value(name)' | wc -l)
  echo "$s: $versions version(s)"
done
```
Every secret must have ≥1 version. Stripe + Sentry come back in §4 and §3.7.

### 3.7 Sentry (optional but recommended)

Create a project in Sentry. Copy the DSN. Then:

```bash
read -rsp "Sentry DSN: " SENTRY_DSN ; echo
printf '%s' "$SENTRY_DSN" | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-sentry-dsn --data-file=-
```

If you skip Sentry, still create an empty version so the Cloud Run secret
mount doesn't 500 on startup:

```bash
printf '' | gcloud secrets versions add {{PROJECT_NAME}}-sentry-dsn --data-file=-
```

