## 6. Database migrations

The first deploy of a Cloud Run revision does NOT run Alembic migrations.
Run them once, manually, via a one-shot Cloud Run Job or local Cloud SQL
Auth Proxy.

**Local approach (easier first time):**

```bash
# Install proxy: https://cloud.google.com/sql/docs/postgres/sql-proxy
./cloud-sql-proxy "$SQL_CONNECTION_NAME" &
PROXY_PID=$!

export DATABASE_URL="postgresql+asyncpg://${DB_USER}:${DB_PASSWORD}@127.0.0.1:5432/${DB_NAME}"
uv run alembic upgrade head

kill $PROXY_PID
```

**Verify:** Connect with `psql` and `\dt` should list every table your
schema declares plus `alembic_version`.

---

## 7. Cloud Scheduler cron jobs (skip if you don't have cron)

Now that the service is up, register any periodic admin calls.

First, grant the scheduler SA invoker rights on this specific service:

```bash
SCHEDULER_SA="{{PROJECT_NAME}}-scheduler@${PROJECT_ID}.iam.gserviceaccount.com"

gcloud run services add-iam-policy-binding "$SERVICE_NAME" \
  --region="$REGION" \
  --member="serviceAccount:${SCHEDULER_SA}" \
  --role=roles/run.invoker
```

Then create your jobs. Example pattern (replace the URI path with your
actual admin endpoint, and the schedule with the cron expression you need):

```bash
CRON_SECRET_VALUE=$(gcloud secrets versions access latest --secret={{PROJECT_NAME}}-cron-secret)

gcloud scheduler jobs create http {{PROJECT_NAME}}-example-job \
  --location="$REGION" \
  --schedule="*/5 * * * *" \
  --uri="${SERVICE_URL}/api/admin/example" \
  --http-method=POST \
  --headers="X-Cron-Secret=${CRON_SECRET_VALUE}" \
  --oidc-service-account-email="$SCHEDULER_SA" \
  --oidc-token-audience="${SERVICE_URL}/api/admin/example"
```

**Verify by forcing a run:**

```bash
gcloud scheduler jobs run {{PROJECT_NAME}}-example-job --location="$REGION"
gcloud logging read 'resource.type=cloud_run_revision
  AND resource.labels.service_name='"$SERVICE_NAME"'
  AND httpRequest.requestUrl=~"example"' \
  --limit=5 --format='value(timestamp,httpRequest.status)'
# Expect: 200 status
```

